A man: "What is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to search for radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
Thanks to these listeners, the effects of atoms released in minerals by radioactivity can truly be heard."
Evans: "Say, it's safe to jump here!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd anniversary.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to "detect" cancer cells
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to "detect" and kill cancer cells
As part of the treatment, the vaccine tells the immune system how to recognize cancer cells
This technique consists of extracting and modifying immune cells from a patient in a laboratory
They can then "detect" a protein that is common to many cancers, and are then reinjected
An experimental vaccine shows encouraging results in patients with different types of cancer.
One woman who received the vaccine, whose goal is to teach the immune system to recognize cancer cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method is to extract and modify one patient's immune cells into a laboratory, so that they can detect HER2 protein, common to many cancers, and finally reinject them.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the American National Cancer Institute based in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine."
According to Professor Berzofsky, the HER2 protein "leads to an increase in various types of cancer," including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer.
A similar approach, consisting of removing immune cells to "learn" to target cancer cells, has been demonstrated in the treatment of a type of leukaemia.
