The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a New Internet to challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a new company that seeks to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee's Solid-Free Platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored as well as people who are allowed to access such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee said that Inrupt was intended to "dominate the world".
"We have to do it now," he said about the launch.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology to enable people to create their own "online personal data store" or DPL.
It may contain contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available at the same time on one browser.
The particularity of the personal data store online is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what type of information.
The company calls this "personal responsibility through data".
According to the CEO of the company, John Bruce, Inrupt's idea is that the company provides adequate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company is currently composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few developers working on the project and a community of voluntary co-ordinators.
Starting this week, technological developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee has stated that his team and they are not yet in discussion with " Facebook and Google" in order to know whether or not to make a complete change where all their business models are completely camouflaged in a moment.
"We do not ask their permission."
In an article published on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee writes that "the mission [d'Inrupt] is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem in order to protect the integrity and quality of the new website built on Solid".
In 1994, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium.
