The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highlands area seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these single flying mammals and will guide future conservation activities.
The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-earned brown bats and Daubenton in the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
Professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat screams as well as the activities of different species.
A map and a report on habitat will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, the populations of bats have declined considerably during the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development that affect perch and cause loss of their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also represent a risk, as can the mower paper and certain chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as the attacks of company cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to identify insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only reserve of Scottish bats on the Thrave site in Dumfries-et-Gallow, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
David Thompson, the domain manager, says that the site is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Threeve, we have an ideal place for bats," he says.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still much to learn about bats, so that the work we do here and elsewhere will help us to better understand what bats need to prosper."
It stresses the importance of verifying the presence of bats before maintaining properties, because by destroying it without wanting a single maternity nest, 400 females and small females can be killed, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perch.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scotland's head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
